@article{burger_effects_1998,
	abstract = {Incubation temperature in ectothermic vertebrates aects incubation periods, and in some reptiles it aects sex ratios and behavior. I present evidence that incubation temperature aects emergence and post-hatching behavior of pine snakes (Pituophis melanoleucus) that could in¯uence survival in the weeks before hibernation. Hatchlings incubated at low temperatures remained in the nest longer, had fewer alternate nest openings, and fewer underground tunnels to hide in than did hatchlings from warmer temperatures. These conditions could render hatchlings from lowtemperature nests more vulnerable to predation because, if a nest is opened, they are not inside tunnels where they would be protected. Hatchlings from nests incubated at low temperatures took longer to {\textregistered}nd shade during a thermoregulation test, and were less likely to move about in search of other cover than were those from higher-incubation-temperature arti{\textregistered}cial nests. Similarly, hatchlings from nests with low incubation temperatures were less responsive to a predatory stimulus and had a longer latency to strike than other hatchlings. Taken together, hatchlings from nests with low incubation temperatures might be less able to avoid predators and {\textregistered}nd shade than those from nests incubated at higher temperatures, and thus could be expected to have lower survival in nature.},
